In Signs and Seasons, Paul, speaking of Meribah, says, “Here the rebellious children made me jealous with strange gods.” That is the difficult thing; when we reject the Lord and turn to other pots, other ink pens, other things that can write and bring us into problems—this is a collective problem. It is not just one person. How then should we respond to temptation that comes our way? The rest of the Song of Moses says that “there [are] not that brings out [their] clothes for repining.” Those who rebel do not have clothes for coming back into fellowship. But the second part, “Neither does he that folds his hands [handkerchiefs, a function of repentance] rejoice in His [the Lord's] work.”

When we are handed over into infirmity and rebellion, we can return to Him by confessing our sin. But, we must ask what it means to “fears” the Lord. Moses uses the Hebrew word “yare", “yareth [as in our church name 2000 years ago, Yar + edeen, from yare' to fear]. It's deeply hidden in Scripture and it pervades the prophets, where when Daniel speaks of sacrifice and how the Lord's sacrifice is superior because no man can give anything that he himself does not possess, and thus, his sacrifice is the sin offering, and this is His blood.

A
